docs.abstract: In 1952, a team of doctors from Harper Hospital and employees from General Motors engineered a mechanical pump that helped pave the way for modern open-heart surgery.
docs.snippet: In 1952, a team of doctors from Harper Hospital and employees from General Motors engineered a mechanical pump that helped pave the way for modern open-heart surgery.
docs.lead_paragraph: As they still do, General Motors cars cruised the streets in the shadow of Detroit’s Harper Hospital in 1952. Above them was the room of Henry Opitek, a cardiac patient who would come to owe his life to the engineers who built those cars — and who helped foster a partnership between the automotive and medical industries that continues today.

headline.main: When Detroit Muscle Powered a Breakthrough in Heart Surgery
headline.print_headline: Detroit’s Shift From Muscle Cars to the Heart Muscle

docs.abstract: It’s long been believed that inflation and higher interest rates are bad for stock prices. Now, it’s unclear how the markets will react.
docs.snippet: It’s long been believed that inflation and higher interest rates are bad for stock prices. Now, it’s unclear how the markets will react.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two weeks ago, fears of higher-than-expected inflation and interest rates sent stocks into a historic and nerve-rattling plunge. This week, those fears were borne out: Consumer prices rose more than expected in January, and interest rates jumped.

headline.main: Inflation and Stocks Are Both Up, and That’s Stirring Some Worries
headline.print_headline: Jitters Rising, With Stocks And Inflation
